":"1574","15 Oct 1599":"15 October 1599","Bef 31 March 1601":"before 31 March 1601","1605":"1605","1625":"1625","Westminster, London, England":"Westminster, Middlesex, England","Stepney, Middlesex, England":"Stepney, Middlesex, England","Stepney, Middlesex, England, United Kingdom":"Stepney, Middlesex, England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Carter","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English: occupational name for a transporter of goods, from Middle English <i>carter(e)</i> ‘carter’ (Anglo-Norman French <i>car(e)tier</i>, Old French <i>charetier</i>, medieval Latin <i>carettarius</i>, <i>carettator</i>). The Old French word coalesced with the earlier Middle English word <i>cart(e)</i> ‘cart’, which is from either Old Norse <i>kartr</i> or Old English <i>cræt</i>, both of which, like the Late Latin word, were probably derived from Celtic. This surname is also very common among African Americans.","Irish: shortened form of   McCarter  .","Americanized form of German   Karter   ‘carder’."],"variants":[{"name":"Charman","meanings":["English (Sussex and Surrey): occupational name for a carter, carrier, or coachman, from Middle English (Old French) <i>char</i>, <i>car</i> ‘car, cart, carriage’ + Middle English <i>man</i> ‘man’. Compare   Carter   and   Carman   2.","English (Sussex and Surrey): occupational name for someone who did odd jobs, from Middle English <i>char(re)</i>, <i>chere</i> (Old English <i>cier(r)</i>, <i>cer(r)</i>, <i>cear(r)</i>, <i>cær(r)</i>) ‘turn (of activity), small job, chore’ + <i>man</i>. Compare   Carman   2.","In some cases probably also an Americanized form of Slovenian <b>Čarman</b> (see   Carman   5)."]},{"name":"Chartier","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  French Andre, Armand, Normand, Jacques, Marcel, Adelard, Alcide, Emile, Gilles, Raoul, Rosaire, Alphonse.","French: shortened form of <i>charretier</i>, an occupational name for a carter, from an agent derivative of Old French <i>charette</i> ‘cart’.","French Canadian: altered form of English   Carter  , a cognate of 1 above. Compare   Sharkey   and   Shorkey  ."]},{"name":"Karter","meanings":["German: occupational name for a carder (someone who prepares wool for spinning), from Middle High German <i>karter</i>. Compare   Carter  ."]},{"name":"McCarter","meanings":["Scottish and northern Irish: variant of   McArthur  ."]},{"name":"Carrier","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  French Armand, Andre, Marcel, Emile, Lucien, Cecile, Alain, Gaetan, Gilles, Jacques, Laurent, Normand.","English and southern French: from Middle English, Old French <i>car(r)ier</i> (from Late Latin <i>carrarius</i>, a derivative of <i>carrum</i> ‘cart, wagon’, a word of Gaulish origin), an occupational name for a carter (see   Carter  ), in French also for a cartwright. Compare French   Charrier  .","French: occupational name for a stonemason or quarryman, <i>carrier</i>. Compare   Coyer  ."]},{"name":"Cartman","meanings":["English (Yorkshire and Lancashire): occupational name from Middle English <i>cartman</i> ‘man who operated a cart for the transport of goods’. Compare   Carter  .","Americanized form of German <b>Kartmann</b> (see   Kartman  )."]}]},{"name":"Thomas","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["New Testament name, borne by one of Christ's twelve apostles, referred to as ‘Thomas, called Didymus’ (John 11:16; 20:24). <i>Didymos</i> is the Greek word for ‘twin’, and the name is the Greek form of an Aramaic byname meaning ‘twin’. The given name has always been popular throughout Christendom, in part because St Thomas's doubts have made him seem a very human character."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705212,"age":18,"year":"1620","julianDay":2312753,"title":"The Pilgrims Board the Mayflower","description":"\"The Pilgrims boarded the Mayflower in search of religious freedom in the New World in September 1620. The Mayflower set sail from Plymouth, England, with 102 passengers, 40 of whom called themselves \"\"Saints.\"\" After two stormy months at sea, the ship reached the New World. Nearly half of the group died during their first winter due to malnutrition and the harsh New England winter.\"","url":"https://www.themayflowersociety.org/the-pilgrims/pilgrim-history","urlTitle":"The Mayflower Society - Pilgrim History","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"When Thomas Carter was born before 31 March 1601, in Westminster, London, England, United Kingdom, his father, William Carter, was 27 and his mother, Martha Rainan, was 21. He had at least 4 sons and 1 daughter with Joane Smith. He died in 1625, in Westminster, Middlesex, England."},"et":{"Bef 31 March 1601–1625":"enne 31. märtsi 1601–1625","1601–1625":"1601–1625","1600–1625":"1600–1625","1621–1677":"1621–1677","–Male":"Surnud","–Female":"Surnud","1574–1605":"1574–1605","1580–1605":"1580–1605","6 Aug 1609":"6. august 1609","1580":"1580","1601":"1601","31 March 1601":"31. märts 1601","1677":"1677","1600":"1600","1621":"1621","1620":"1620","1574":"1574","15 Oct 1599":"15. oktoober 1599","Bef 31 March 1601":"enne 31. märtsi 1601","1605":"1605","1625":"1625","Westminster, London, England":"Westminster, Middlesex, England","Stepney, Middlesex, England":"Stepney, Middlesex, England","Stepney, Middlesex, England, United Kingdom":"Stepney, Middlesex, Inglismaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"Bef 31 March 1601–1625":"ennen vuotta 31. maaliskuuta 1601–1625","1601–1625":"1601–1625","1600–1625":"1600–1625","1621–1677":"1621–1677","–Male":"Kuollut","–Female":"Kuollut","1574–1605":"1574–1605","1580–1605":"1580–1605","6 Aug 1609":"6. elokuuta 1609","1580":"1580","1601":"1601","31 March 1601":"31. maaliskuuta 1601","1677":"1677","1600":"1600","1621":"1621","1620":"1620","1574":"1574","15 Oct 1599":"15. lokakuuta 1599","Bef 31 March 1601":"ennen vuotta 31. maaliskuuta 1601","1605":"1605","1625":"1625","Westmin